    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nWhen running nvim (from st+tmux+zsh), and then suspending it with control-z (to do shell work), system loadavg starts to rise and continues rising as long as nvim is suspended. Once resumed, loadavg starts to drop back to normal.\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\nRunning `st` terminal, where `tmux` window is running `zsh` shell.\r\nStart nvim.\r\nSuspend nvim with `ctrl-z`\r\nStart `top` (on other window) and observe loadavg rising.\r\nResume nvim (with `fg`) on orignal window.\r\nOn `top` observe how loadavg starts to fall.\r\n\r\n#### Addition\r\n\r\nAlso tried with just `xterm` and `bash` (so, without st+tmux+zsh combo) and result is same, skyrocketing loadavg.\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nWhen suspended, neovim should not cause loadavg to start rise (and cause system gradually to slowdown).\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\n0.9.1 (release)\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nNope, this is just nvim process problem.\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nArch Linux\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nst 0.8.4\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nscreen-256color\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nextra/neovim using pacman",
